  "prompt": "Can all engines be overbored? What engines cannot be overbored?",
  "response": "Not all engines can be overbored. Overboring an engine involves enlarging the cylinder bore diameter to increase the engine's displacement, potentially boosting performance. However, whether an engine can be overbored depends on several factors, including the engine's design, the thickness and material of the cylinder walls, and the engine block's structural integrity.\n\nEngines that typically cannot be overbored include:\n\n1. **Engines with Thin Cylinder Walls**: Overboring such engines could compromise the structural integrity of the cylinder walls, leading to failure.\n\n2. **Aluminum Block Engines**: Many aluminum blocks have thin liners or special coatings that make them unsuitable for overboring without compromising durability.\n\n3. **Engine Blocks with Integrated Cylinder Liners**: Some modern engines use cylinder liners that are integrated into the engine block. Removing or enlarging these liners can be impractical and unfeasible.\n\n4. **High-Performance Engines**: These engines might already be optimized to their limits, and overboring could negatively affect their reliability and performance.\n\n5. **Engines with Nikasil or Similar Coatings**: Coated cylinders (such as Nikasil) are difficult to overbore due to the coating process. Removing the coating can damage the cylinders and impair performance.\n\nBefore considering overboring an engine, it's essential to consult with an expert or refer to the manufacturer's specifications to determine if overboring is a feasible and safe option for your specific engine.",
